node.text:

.

If you are struggling to break free from exercise compulsion I’m sending so much compassion your way.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jennifer Rollin, MSW, LCSW-C on August 22, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Jennifer Rollin @jennifer_rollin How is it 2021 and not all therapists are trauma-informed? ALL therapy should be trauma informed.'.

node.text:
Content warning: talking about trauma
.
From the older male therapist I was seeing when I was sexually assaulted in college who didn’t even label it as assault-to the therapist I saw years ago who kept prodding with questions about the trauma when I was clearly dissociated and highly triggered by her questions.
.
ALL therapy should be trauma informed, and in order to actually be trauma informed should also be social justice informed.
.
Especially given how prevalent trauma is and the ability to cause harm.
.
While of course the trauma never goes away, I’m grateful to no longer experience PTSD symptoms. But sad that it took so long for me to get proper therapy and support. 
.

May be an image of text that says 'Jennifer Rollin @jennifer_rollin Teenage boy on TikTok "your account is just for people who under-eat not for people who binge and lack self control." Me: physical and emotional restriction is one of the top triggers for binge eating. So yes, talking about eating what you are craving is applicable to BED too.'.

node.text:
Multiple times on TikTok people have said “well this doesn’t apply to people who binge” about my posts.
.
Which demonstrates a fundamental lack of understanding of binge eating.
.
Binge eating was one of the eating disorder symptoms that I personally struggled with and I have a lot of professional experience in treating it.
.
The main triggers for binge eating are restriction (emotional or physical), habituation, emotional factors, trauma, and what I call “the F it mentality” which is also related to food rules.
.
People who binge don’t ‘lack willpower’ and trying to heal bingeing by attempting to exert “more willpower” does not work.
.
It’s also important to note the anti fat attitudes come into play-where it’s assumed that everyone in a larger body binges and anti fat stereotypes such as ‘lacking control’ etc are applied to folks in larger bodies. And of course the ‘hierarchy’ of eating disorder behaviors and lack of respect folks with BED and folks in larger bodies (regardless of ED diagnosis) often experience in ED treatment. This is NOT at all ok.
.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jennifer Rollin, MSW, LCSW-C on August 21, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Jennifer Rollin @jennifer_rollin Why is people saying 'I'm taking better care of my health' most often a euphemism for trying to lose weight. Like why can't it be I'm working on wearing sunscreen daily flossing more, going to therapy, and working on self care for stress?'.

node.text:
Things you can do to ‘improve health’ without trying to shrink your body:
.
•spend time with friends
•nourish your body regularly with yummy food
•make gratitude lists
•go to therapy
•set boundaries
•practice self compassion 
•wear sunscreen
•floss regularly 
•get enough sleep.
•spend time in nature 
•meditate 
•practice mindfulness
•get vaccinated if you are eligible to do so.
•remember to take psych meds (if you are prescribed them).
.
Also health isn’t a moral imperative and some people for instance folks with chronic illnesses may never be ‘healthy’ and you are no less valuable!
.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jennifer Rollin, MSW, LCSW-C on August 20, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Jennifer Rollin @jennifer_rollin What eating disorder therapist or dietitian goes 'ah look a photo of me when I was unwell in my eating disorder' next to me now, let me share this with my vulnerable following of people in recovery, that'll be helpful.' Like just don't get it.'.

node.text:
Of course people have to learn how to cope with triggers, however we don’t have to purposely share these kinds of images. I can’t imagine the tailspin it would have sent me in when I was in recovery if someone on my treatment team posted a before and after picture of their body in recovery.
.
Before posting anything I ask myself how will this help and how might it harm? When research and lived experience suggests that these kinds of photos are harmful for many folks in recovery-why share?
.
Before and after photos can be stigmatizing, reinforce the idea of not sick enough, often perpetuates the myth that we can tell who has an ED by what they look like, highlight more body emphasis, and have never been proven to be widely helpful to folks in recovery. And often the ‘after’ is like ‘look at me, I’m still thin!’
.
I honestly feel like professionals post them because they tend to ‘do well’ on social media vs what is actually helpful for their audience. Or to try to validate an unhealed part of themselves. Regardless of the reason-it’s always good to look at potential for benefit vs potential for harm before posting.
.
Once we know better, we can do better. 👊🏻
.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jennifer Rollin, MSW, LCSW-C on August 19, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Jennifer Rollin @jennifer_rollin The word 'cellulite' was invented in France in the 19th century. People didn't see it as a 'problem' until the media started saying that it was. Diet culture seized the opportunity to sell creams and procedures that claim to 'treat' what is a made up 'problem.''.

node.text:
History sure is interesting! 
.
Love how ‘problems’ are created to sell us ‘solutions.’ 🤦‍♀️
.
Via Kelsey Miller “until relatively recently, there was no word to define it, because “it” was not a thing. Half a century ago, no one in this country had even heard of cellulite, let alone identified it as a problem to be gotten rid of. Today, we spend untold millions — if not billions — on anti-cellulite treatments, despite the glaring lack of evidence that any of them work. Which makes perfect sense, of course, because you cannot treat a condition that doesn’t actually exist.”
.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jennifer Rollin, MSW, LCSW-C on August 19, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Jennifer Rollin @jennifer_rollir At a waxing appointment, the woman mentioned if| wanted to get 'rid of the sun damage' on my face, she does chemical peels. This 'problem' was something i'd never considered before. And her chemical peels cost 400 dollars. This is exactly how the beauty industry works.'.

node.text:
She went on to say how my skin would look more beautiful for my wedding and some other stuff.
.
I feel mixed about this. On one hand, I get that she’s trying to sell her services. On the other hand, I think there’s a way to promote services without pointing out what you perceive as ‘flaws’ on someone.
.
At the end of the day, I don’t fault her-I fault the beauty industry and diet culture as a whole.
.
For instance, cellulite wasn’t seen as ‘a problem’ until someone invented a cream alleging to ‘help reduce it.’
.
The beauty industry and diet culture often ‘creates problems’ to then try to ‘sell you a solution.’
.
**i’m not speaking to every provider just the over arching themes of the industry (where I’m talking about big billion dollar corporations) re anti aging and fat phobia etc-not saying every beauty industry provider is problematic! As there are some lovely ones. ❤️
.
